<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Curated"><PMID Version="1">41316551</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2025</Year><Month>11</Month><Day>29</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2025</Year><Month>12</Month><Day>19</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1532-9283</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>45</Volume><PubDate><Year>2025</Year><Month>Dec</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Journal of bodywork and movement therapies</Title><ISOAbbreviation>J Bodyw Mov Ther</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Effect of cold compression and ice therapy on muscle recovery after plyometric exercise: A randomized crossover trial.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>1010</StartPage><EndPage>1019</EndPage><MedlinePgn>1010-1019</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1016/j.jbmt.2025.10.021</ELocationID><ELocationID EIdType="pii" ValidYN="Y">S1360-8592(25)00413-9</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="OBJECTIVES" NlmCategory="OBJECTIVE">This study aimed to assess the effects of cold compression therapy (Game Ready&#xae;), ice, and placebo on quadriceps recovery in amateur football players following plyometric exercise, focusing on stiffness, reactive strength index (RSI), pain, and muscle damage markers.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="DESIGN" NlmCategory="METHODS">Randomized, controlled, crossover trial.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="SETTING" NlmCategory="METHODS">University biomechanics laboratory.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="PARTICIPANTS" NlmCategory="METHODS">Forty-five healthy male amateur football players.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="MAIN OUTCOME MEASURES" NlmCategory="METHODS">Muscle stiffness (N/m), RSI, pressure pain threshold (PPT), perfusion (perfusion units, PU), creatine kinase (CK), lactate dehydrogenase (LDH), and total quality recovery (TQR), assessed at pre, post, 24&#xa0;h, 48&#xa0;h, and 72&#xa0;h after plyometric exercise.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="RESULTS" NlmCategory="RESULTS">Cold compression significantly reduced muscle stiffness (p&#xa0;&lt;&#xa0;0.01), CK and LDH levels (p&#xa0;&lt;&#xa0;0.05), and improved RSI (p&#xa0;&lt;&#xa0;0.01) and PU (p&#xa0;&lt;&#xa0;0.01) at 48&#xa0;h and 72&#xa0;h, compared to placebo. No significant differences were found between groups in PPT.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="CONCLUSIONS" NlmCategory="CONCLUSIONS">Cold compression therapy was more effective than ice or placebo in promoting muscle recovery after plyometric exercise by enhancing perfusion, reducing muscle stiffness and biochemical damage, and improving neuromuscular performance and perceived recovery.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>Copyright &#xa9; 2025 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Trybulski</LastName><ForeName>Robert</ForeName><Initials>R</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Medical Department, Wojciech Korfanty Upper Silesian Academy, 40-659, Katowice, Poland; Provita Medical Center, &#x17b;ory, Poland. Electronic address: trybulski.research@gmail.com.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Muracki</LastName><ForeName>Jaros&#x142;aw</ForeName><Initials>J</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Institute of Physical Culture Sciences, Department of Physical Culture and Health, University of Szczecin, 70-453, Szczecin, Poland. Electronic address: jaroslaw.muracki@usz.edu.pl.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Aldhahi</LastName><ForeName>Monira I</ForeName><Initials>MI</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Rehabilitation Sciences, College of Health and Rehabilitation Sciences, Princess Nourah bint Abdulrahman University, P.O. Box 84428, Riyadh, 11671, Saudi Arabia. Electronic address: mialdhahi@pnu.edu.sa.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><L